From Dan Sorenson Subject Re Flashing anyone Chris BeHanna writes Just before arriving at a toll booth I switch the hazards on I do thisto warn other motorists that I will be taking longer than the seconds to make the transaction My question, is this a good bad thing to do This sounds like a VERY good thing to do I'll second that In addition, I find my hazards to be more often used than my horn At speeds below mph on the interstates, quite common in mountains with trucks, some states require flashers In rural areas, flashers let the guy behind you know there is a tractor with a rather large implement behind it in the way Use them whenever you need to communicate that things will deviate from the norm Chris BeHanna DoD H D FXWG Wide Glide Jubilee's Red Lady CB T Baby Bike Disclaimer Now why would NEC ZX needs a name Is that ZX painted green Since the green Triumph that a friend owned was sold off, her name is now free for adoption How does the name Thunderpickle grab you Dan Sorenson, DoD ISU only censors what I read, not what I say Don't blame them USENET Post to exotic, distant machines Meet exciting, unusual people And flame them